ca.cgjennings.ui.textedit.completion

Class ScriptCompletionContext

  • java.lang.Object
    • ca.cgjennings.ui.textedit.completion.ScriptCompletionContext

  • public class ScriptCompletionContext
extends Object
    Describes the context in which a scripting code completion occurs. The context consists of these elements:

    First the context captures the sequence of dot expressions and function calls that prefix the caret. For each subexpression, users can look up the identifier with getIdentifier(int) and the number of arguments with getParameterCount(int) (which is -1 if the subexpression is just an identifier). To get the remainder of the subexpression that follows the caret, call getSuffix(). For example, the following expression would consist of the listed values: 

     alpha.beta.gamma( mu, nu ).del|ta    (where | is the caret)

                   i    0     1      2     3
     getIdentifier(i) alpha  beta  gamma  del
 getParameterCount(i)  -1     -1     2    -1

 getSuffix() = ta

    Second, the context includes boolean flags about the syntactic structure that the caret is found in. The names of these methods start with inside. For example insideNewOperator() returns true when the user is competing code after the new operator. (In which case, the completer should return the names of constructors.)

    Since:
    3.0

    • Method Detail

      • getIdentifier

        public String getIdentifier(int index)
        Returns the identifier at the specified index. If this is size()-1, then the identifier includes the text up to the caret position. The identifier text following the caret can be retrieved by calling getSuffix().
        Parameters:
        index - the index of the identifier segment
        Returns:
        the identifier at the specified segment, or identifier start for the last segment

      • getParameterCount

        public int getParameterCount(int index)
        Returns the number of parameters used by the function call that occurs within the specified segment. If the segment does not represent a function call, returns -1. For example, the following would have three segments with the parameter counts [2,-1,0]: 
        alpha(x,y).beta.gamma()
        Parameters:
        index - the index of the identifier segment
        Returns:
        the number of parameters passed to the function call at that index, or -1

      • getPrefix

        public String getPrefix()
        Returns the prefix immediately before the caret. This is simply the last identifier segment. For example, the following expression has prefix "gam": 
        alpha.beta.gam|ma
        Returns:
        the part of the last identifier segment up to the caret; i.e. the last identifier segment
        See Also:
        getSuffix()

      • getSuffix

        public String getSuffix()
        Returns the identifier text that follows the caret, or an empty string if there is none. The following expression has suffix "ma": 
        alpha.beta.gam|ma
        Returns:
        the part of the last identifier segment that comes after the caret and is not included in the last segment string

      • insideStringLiteral

        public boolean insideStringLiteral()
        Returns true if the caret is in a string literal. This is provided mainly for completing useLibrary calls; in other cases the literal may not be detected and the context will be an empty expression. When this is true, there is a single identifier and it will start with the quote character that begins the string literal in the source. The suffix will be blank. Since the literal is usually unclosed when completing code, the intended string end cannot be known for certain.

      • insideUseLibrary

        public boolean insideUseLibrary()
        Returns true if the caret is inside the parentheses of a call to useLibrary.

      • isFromScopeRoot

        public boolean isFromScopeRoot()
        Returns true if the sequence of names begins by looking up something in scope. If this returns false, then at some point the expression became an arbitrary object that cannot be traced from the scope with the available information.
        Returns:
        whether the expression includes reflective property lookups

      • size

        public int size()
        Returns the number of identifiers in the expression. For example, if the editor looks like the following, returns 3: 
        Eons.window.di|
        Returns:
        the id count

        Returns a string representation of the context for debugging.

        Returns:
